## Why This Is Asked
Tests fundamental React Native bridging concepts, platform-specific API integration, and event stream management with proper lifecycle handling.

## Key Concepts
- React Native native modules and TurboModule architecture
- Platform APIs: iOS UIDevice battery monitoring, Android BatteryManager
- Event emitters and lifecycle cleanup
- Throttling strategies to preserve battery life

## Code Example
```javascript
// Example JS usage
import { NativeModules, NativeEventEmitter } from 'react-native';
const { BatteryMonitor } = NativeModules;
const emitter = new NativeEventEmitter(BatteryMonitor);

// Initialize monitor
BatteryMonitor.initMonitor({ intervalMs: 5000 });

// Listen for battery changes
const subscription = emitter.addListener('onBatteryChange', (batteryInfo) => {
  console.log('Battery level:', batteryInfo.level);
  console.log('Is charging:', batteryInfo.isCharging);
});

// Start monitoring
BatteryMonitor.startMonitoring();

// Get current battery state
const currentBattery = BatteryMonitor.getCurrentBattery();

// Stop monitoring and cleanup
BatteryMonitor.stopMonitoring();
subscription.remove();
```

## Platform Differences
**iOS**: Uses UIDevice notifications, requires enabling battery monitoring, provides state change notifications automatically.

**Android**: Uses broadcast receivers for battery changes, requires explicit polling with timers, more granular battery information available.

## Power Implications
- Frequent polling drains battery; use appropriate intervals
- iOS notifications are event-driven and more efficient
- Android requires careful background task management
- Consider throttling updates and cleanup on app backgrounding

