## Why This Is Asked

This question tests cross-platform native module design, covering model loading, thread management, memory control, and privacy. It probes data marshaling between JS and native layers, lifecycle management, and the ability to handle streaming inference workloads.

## Key Concepts

- TurboModule / JSI integration for high-performance native-JS communication
- Cross-platform backend: TF Lite on Android, Core ML on iOS
- Dedicated worker thread with a ring buffer for input queueing
- Memory budgeting and backpressure via bounded queues
- Privacy-conscious data handling: keep inference on-device, avoid unnecessary data copies

## Code Example

```javascript
// Usage sketch
import { RNMLInference } from 'react-native-ml-infer';

async function runInference() {
  // Initialize the model on a dedicated worker thread
  await RNMLInference.startModel('/models/classifier.tflite', [1, 224, 224, 3], [1, 1000]);

  // Stream input frames and receive results via callback
  RNMLInference.onResult((result) => {
    console.log('Inference result:', result);
  });

  // Feed streaming input (e.g., camera frames)
  for (const frame of cameraStream) {
    await RNMLInference.feedInput(frame);
  }

  // Cleanup when done
  await RNMLInference.stopModel();
}
```

## Thread-Safety & Backpressure

- **Thread Safety**: Use atomic operations or lock-free data structures for the input queue; the worker thread consumes inputs while JS pushes them. Ensure all native object access is guarded by mutexes or serialization queues.
- **Backpressure**: Implement a bounded ring buffer. When the queue is full, either drop the oldest entry or signal back to JS to slow production. This prevents unbounded memory growth.
- **Lifecycle Cleanup**: Invalidate the worker thread on stopModel(); use std::promise/std::future or React Native's native module lifecycle callbacks (invalidate()) to ensure all threads terminate and memory is freed before the module is unloaded.

